<h1 align=center>Calcium Channel Blockers </h1>

<h3>The Calcium Channel Blockers (examples: nifedipine, verapamil, diltiazem)
inhibit the flow of calcium into the cardiac (heart) and smooth muscle
cells. This action accounts for their effects of lowering blood pressure,
relieving angina (chest pain) and stabilizing certain abnormal heart rhythyms.
</h3>

<p>
<hr></p>

<h3><a href="disclaim.htm">INDICATIONS</a></h3>

<li>angina </li>

<li>atrial fibrillation </li>

<li>atrial flutter </li>

<li>diabetic nephropathy </li>

<li>heart failure+ </li>

<li>hiccups+ </li>

<li>hypertension </li>

<li>hypertensive urgency+ </li>

<li>hypertensive emergency+ </li>

<li>mania+ </li>

<li>migraine prophylaxis+ </li>

<li>paroxysmal supraventricular tachycardia </li>

<li>Prinzmetal's angina </li>

<li>proteinuria+ </li>

<li>unstable angina </li>

<dl>
<dd>+ = not an FDA approved indication</dd>
</dl>

<p>
